textDisplay:
@kyleray4952 I think it's more about the setting of all this. In the time that London wrote this story, it was more commonplace for treatment of things like crushed legs or serious illness among animals to be something of or akin to a bullet in the head. The violent aspect may not be the strongest reasoning, but it does set a mood for how the rest of the story proceeds. If it's included, but they don't tell the public, kids might find themselves a tad emotionally scarred. If it's omitted, it loses appeal to the overall story, turning into another shameless cashgrab. Part of what makes Call of the Wild a memorable piece is it's addressing the harsh yet opportune reality of living in such an unforgiving landscape, even among the animals. 

In the book, there is a chapter dealing in hunger, particularly in the hunger of an animal, whether man or beast. The sled team is enduring a spat of infighting, between the established alpha, Spitz and a challenger, Buck. As the struggle comes to a head, the entire camp is beset by wild dogs. These dogs are starved, driven mad by hunger and disease, attacking anyone they pass. Buck is badly wounded, as are the other sled dogs, who flee the camp to the frozen lake beyond. There, the team slowly, carefully make their way back to shore, as the ice is thin. A few occasionally fall in, coming close to drowning or freezing, before clawing back out. Upon regrouping in the woods, they return to the camp and have their wounds tended. The sight of those dogs stays with Buck, their flesh stretched over bones, their eyes wild and their faces skeletal and angry. This is further emphasized when Dolly, one of the other wounded dogs, begins attacking Buck and howling like a wild animal. Certain that she is rabid from her bites, driver Francois drives his axe into her head, killing her.

If this movie isn't at least a severe PG13, it'll be a complete bust.

